content.text:
`main.swift` currently does two things:

1. Imports SwiftUI.
2. Defines a minimal `ContentView` that displays the text `"Hello"`.

```swift
import SwiftUI

struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello")
    }
}
```

It does **not** define an app entry point, so by itself it is not a complete SwiftUI app.

## 1. Add an app entry point

```swift
import SwiftUI

@main
struct HelloApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView()
        }
    }
}
```

This tells Swift where the app starts and shows `ContentView` in the main window.

## 2. Improve readability

```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello")
            .font(.title)
            .padding()
    }
}
```

This expands the one-line view into a more readable structure and adds simple styling.

## 3. Add a `#Preview`

```swift
#Preview {
    ContentView()
}
```

This enables SwiftUI previews in Xcode so you can quickly inspect `ContentView` while developing.
